{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614296"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:43:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:43:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16355"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16355"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.73,0,0.15,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114425"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9046"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96426"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7195"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21516"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114425"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cranial nerves have nuclei located at various levels within the brainstem. Some nerves have multiple nuclei spanning different regions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves has nuclei located within the midbrain, pons, and medulla?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trochlear nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Abducens nerve","Facial nerve","Vestibulocochlear nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is unique in having nuclei that span all three levels of the brainstem: midbrain (mesencephalic nucleus for proprioception), pons (principal sensory nucleus and motor nucleus), and medulla (spinal trigeminal nucleus for pain and temperature). This extensive distribution reflects its complex functions in sensory (touch, pain, temperature, proprioception) and motor (mastication) control of the face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E has its nucleus only in the midbrain. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eabducens nerve\u003C/strong\u003E has its nucleus only in the pons. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E has its nuclei primarily in the pons. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibulocochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E has its nuclei in the pons and medulla only.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The trigeminal nerve (CN V) has nuclei spanning multiple levels of the brainstem including the midbrain, pons, and medulla.","The main trigeminal nuclei are the motor nucleus (pons), principal sensory nucleus (pons), and spinal trigeminal nucleus (medulla).","The mesencephalic nucleus of CN V in the midbrain processes proprioceptive information from jaw muscles."],"references":["Huff T, Weisbrod LJ, Daly DT. Neuroanatomy, Cranial Nerve 5 (Trigeminal). 2024 Apr 20. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29489263.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions"